**Documentation, oh documentation  
How many use your "outdated" reputation as an excuse not to write you at all?**

<Spacer />

Hi. Do you write documentation?  
If you do, how did you start?

I still remember the first time I was asked to write documentation at work.  
Back then, my manager wasnâ€™t exactly encouraging engineers to write docs.

Why?  
Probably because documentation needs regular updatesâ€”or it goes stale.  
Worse, outdated or conflicting docs can create a mess thatâ€™s more harmful than helpful.

Would you have just accepted that answer?  
I couldnâ€™t.

The manager wasnâ€™t banning documentationâ€”just not promoting it.  
Thatâ€™s a big difference. And I guess Iâ€™m the kind of person who likes to push the edges of whatâ€™s allowed.

Thatâ€™s when I began a line of thought Iâ€™d later call:  
**What documentation means to software engineering.**


## Start with â€œSoftware Engineeringâ€

Letâ€™s break it down: documentation, software engineering, meaning.

Some parts are abstractâ€”too fuzzy to start withâ€”so I began with the more concrete one: â€œSoftware engineering.â€

Have you ever stopped to ask: _What exactly is software engineering?_

In my search, I found a quote I liked from David Lorge Parnas, pioneer of _information hiding_:

> _â€œSoftware engineering is the multi-person development of multi-version programs.â€_

In other words, **software engineering is building evolving programs as a team**.  
Even solo developers collaborateâ€”with their past, present, and future selves.

So being a software engineer isnâ€™t just about writing code.  
Itâ€™s about doing it well in a world of shifting versions and many contributors.


## Then, Letâ€™s Talk About Documentation

So what _is_ documentation?

Some say self-documenting code is a core skillâ€”and a difference between developers and engineers.  
But that still doesnâ€™t answer the question.

In practice, documentation comes in many formsâ€”READMEs, API docs, test reports, specs, diagrams.  
It can be text, images, tables, flowcharts, or a mix.

In the context of software engineering, documentation connects directly to its core nature:  
**multi-person, multi-version collaboration**.

Where people and code are constantly evolving, documentation becomes a bridge across **time and turnover**.

Maybe thatâ€™s its true meaning in software engineering.


## From Concept to Strategy

I know this sounds abstract.  
But for me, laying out a thought process helps me ground decisions in principlesâ€”not just instinct.

In my last job, I convinced my manager to stop blocking docs by lowering the cost of writing them.  
But I still felt I was operating on gut feel.

Yes, I could decide case by case.  
Yes, I could persuade stakeholders.  
But did I have a **documentation investment strategy**?

Especially with limited timeâ€”how do you prioritize whatâ€™s worth documenting?

So in this job, I wanted a framework that created value for both engineering and the business.  
Because not all documentation carries the same weight.

## Three Angles to Evaluate Documentation

While my previous and current managers had different concerns, both cared about efficiency and value.

I broke the problem into three dimensions:

- **Lifecycle**  
  Some docs are short-lived (e.g., project notes); others persist.  
  Knowing the _expected lifespan_ clarifies maintenance needs and ownership.

- **Frequency of Questions**  
  The more often something is asked, the more valuable it is to document.  
  This saves time and surfaces **knowledge gaps**.  
  If one person becomes a bottleneck, itâ€™s time to **scale horizontally** by documenting and sharing.

- **Risk Level**  
  Some topics rarely come upâ€”but when they do, mistakes are costly.  
  These are like evacuation manuals: seldom used, but must be reliable when needed.

## Reducing the Friction of Writing

Once I knew _what_ to document, the next challenge was _how_.

I didnâ€™t want to rely on willpower every time.  
And I didnâ€™t want to be the only one writing.

So I borrowed from requirement and design review workflows and made documentation a **collaborative process**:

- **Define the purpose before writing**  
  Whoâ€™s it for? When will they read it? What problem does it solve?  
  Whatâ€™s their technical background? Whatâ€™s in or out of scope?

- **Start with an outline, not a full doc**  
  This makes reviews easier and avoids overwhelming readers.  
  It lowers the cost of feedback and encourages early alignment.

- **Separate detail from structure**  
  Focus on the readerâ€™s _task_. Move tangents or extras to references or FAQs to keep the main flow clean.


## Documentation as a Bridgeâ€”and a Dialogue

As I worked on reducing the friction, I realized something unexpected:

Documentation isnâ€™t just an output.  
Writing it is a chance to **facilitate discussion and build alignment**.

Collaborating on outlines or examples uncovers mismatched assumptions.  
It turns vague disagreements into something concrete.

Docs become more than knowledge repositories.  
Theyâ€™re tools to drive **conversation**, challenge **assumptions**, and align **mental models**.

In that sense, documenting is just another form of version controlâ€”  
but for _team understanding_.


## Back to the Original Question

Hi again.

Do you write documentation?  
How did you start?

I no longer ask whether we _should_ document, but rather:  
**Whatâ€™s worth documenting?**  
**How do we write meaningfully?**  
**How do we use the process to give teams clarity and direction?**

Because documentation isnâ€™t just knowledge transferâ€”  
itâ€™s how we keep that knowledge from staying locked inside overworked experts.

The meaning of documentation in software engineering might lie in the small choices we make:

- What to preserve  
- Who to preserve it for  
- And how to do it  

The sum of those choices is part of what makes us software engineers.

<Spacer />

Do I know if this way of thinking will lead me where I want to go?  
No.  
I didnâ€™t expect it to get me close to a Staff-level roleâ€”at least not so soon.

But maybe thatâ€™s how it starts.
